Cleaning Data

Author

Schwab

Data is Messy.

We have to clean other people’s data.

Lubridate

Cleans dates for us. cheat-sheet

ymd(),mdy()

library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)

head(lakers$date,3)
[1] 20081028 20081028 20081028

lakers$date

typeof(lakers$date)
[1] "integer"
#This makes no sense
sum(lakers$date)
[1] 695490347999
# Let's make this into a time object.
lakers$date <-ymd(lakers$date)
typeof(lakers$date)
[1] "double"

Now they are dates

lakers_date <- lakers |>
  select(date)
head(lakers_date, 3)
        date
1 2008-10-28
2 2008-10-28
3 2008-10-28

Add time

lakers$date[1]
[1] "2008-10-28"
lakers$date[1] + days(x=12)
[1] "2008-11-09"

You try:

How would we make the time column into a time not a

typeof(lakers$time)
[1] "character"

Tidyr

cheatsheet

lakers_date <- lakers |>
  select(date)
head(lakers_date, 3)
        date
1 2008-10-28
2 2008-10-28
3 2008-10-28

separate dates

Formally separate() but is now separate_wider_delim().

lakers_date |>
  separate_wider_delim(
    cols = date, 
    delim = "-", 
    names = c("year","month","day") )    |>
  head(3)
# A tibble: 3 × 3
  year  month day  
  <chr> <chr> <chr>
1 2008  10    28   
2 2008  10    28   
3 2008  10    28

More Separate

You can use

  • separate_wider_position()

  • separate_wider_regex()

lakers_date |>
  separate_wider_position(cols = "date", widths = c(year=4,1,month=2,1,day=2)
                          )|>
  head(3)
# A tibble: 3 × 3
  year  month day  
  <chr> <chr> <chr>
1 2008  10    28   
2 2008  10    28   
3 2008  10    28

Unite

You can also unite() columns into a new column.

See cheat sheet.

Oh the NAs

  • You can throw out rows NAs with drop_na()

  • You can use fill() to overwrite them with previous values

  • replace_na() to specify a replacement.

str_replace()

You can replace strings within columns.

Consider: the hours_tv_per_day variable from yrbss:

head(yrbss$hours_tv_per_school_day)
[1] "5+" "5+" "5+" "2"  "3"  "5+"

We probably want to get rid of the + symbols in the DF.

str_replace(string = yrbss$hours_tv_per_school_day,
            #Note that the plus is special so we must escapse it
            pattern = "\\+",
            replacement = ""
            )
